00:04:05.230 --> 00:04:07.290
This is what he did.

00:04:07.290 --> 00:04:09.830
You see, Sudokus--

00:04:09.830 --> 00:04:13.880
what you can do is if I took the
first two rows and swapped

00:04:13.880 --> 00:04:17.579
them over, it would still
be a valid Sudoku grid.

00:04:17.579 --> 00:04:18.829
That's allowed, right?

00:04:18.829 --> 00:04:22.200
It's the same, if I took any of
those first three rows and

00:04:22.200 --> 00:04:25.440
swapped them over, you would
get a valid Sudoku grid.

00:04:25.440 --> 00:04:27.710
The same is true for the
next three rows.

00:04:27.710 --> 00:04:30.270
You swap them over, you
get a valid grid.

00:04:30.270 --> 00:04:32.340
And the last three rows.

00:04:32.340 --> 00:04:33.110
You swap them over, you
get a valid grid.

00:04:33.110 --> 00:04:34.170
And these bands as well.

00:04:34.170 --> 00:04:37.940
If you take these as bands and
swap the bands over, you get a

00:04:37.940 --> 00:04:38.810
valid grid.

00:04:38.810 --> 00:04:43.720
So if you had a valid 16 clue
starting position, it would

00:04:43.720 --> 00:04:46.770
still be a valid 16 clue
starting position when you

00:04:46.770 --> 00:04:48.335
start to swap the rows.

00:04:48.335 --> 00:04:51.900
And what you get is a whole
family of Sudokus.

00:04:51.900 --> 00:04:54.020
It's the same for the columns.

00:04:54.020 --> 00:04:57.990
It's the same if I rotate the
grid, and it's the same if I

00:04:57.990 --> 00:04:58.980
